{
  "doc_id": "44230",
  "text": "One of the advantages of the mouse mandible in this context is that it is a model system to study the development and evolution of complex morphological structures [CITATION_1] . This bone structure is made of six different units that differ in their embryological origin, time and rates of differentiation [CITATION_2] . The six parts are grouped in two main functional units, the alveolar region (the distal region of the mouse mandible that houses the teeth) and the ascending ramus (the region that connects the mandible to the skull and in which the masticatory muscles are connected) (Fig. 1) , [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Quantitative trait loci (QTL) analyses have shown a certain degree of genetic independence between these two modules [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
